         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nWhen we look at a recipe, we generally find the list of ingredients that must be added to a container to prepare the food.\n\nOften the dish requires a smaller amount than what is available in the package we bought or in what we gathered from the forest. This leads us to a reflection:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: Better to have too much than too little</b><br /><br />When we move an amount of an ingredient from one place to another, are we performing a mathematical operation?<br /><br />Have you ever stopped to think that the food you consider delicious is only possible because someone has mastered different sciences, even without knowing how to name them?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "When we think that mathematics is just about formulas on paper, we fail to understand what this powerful language of nature truly represents. It is present in every corner of the universe.\n\nA good example of the profound use of mathematics is the act of cooking, whether in the Shona culture (<htcite0>) or in our own home.\n\nIn this text, we will begin to study the mathematics involved in food preparation.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "cc162709-bdc3-469b-a208-e900f4570842",
